export const batch147 = {
  'immune.json': {
    base: { id: 'immune', title: 'Immune', author: '', type: 'summary', addedAt: 1781652336874 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: 'A friend and a foe at once',
        text: 'You planned a night out, but now a stubborn flu has pinned you to the couch. Pain, fever, a runny nose, and a dry cough take over. You blame the weather, the missing scarf, or that late bus ride. In a few days you will feel fine again and meet your friends as if nothing happened.\n\nWhile you lie in bed, an unseen army works hard inside you. Your immune system tracks down viruses and wipes them out, often before you even notice the symptoms. The same force that fights a simple cold also handles deeper threats, such as bacteria that slip into a cut, rogue cancer cells, or a serious infection like COVID-19.\n\nThe trouble is that this system is not a clock. It is complex and unpredictable. One person shakes off a serious infection, another lands in the hospital. During the recent pandemic, many deaths came from an immune response that ran too hot rather than too cold. Predicting who wins and who loses is closer to a coin flip than a science.\n\nModern research has not mapped every detail of this protection. What we do know is how it works at a basic level and how small choices can lift it up or push it down. That knowledge is worth your time, so read on.'
      },
      {
        title: 'A nonstop defender on call',
        text: 'This section covers related book summaries that readers often pair with the immune system topic. The list is short and links to other works on habit formation, study skills, and creative work, including titles by Peter C. Brown, Mark A. McDaniel, Henry L. Roediger, Jocelyn K. Glei, Robert Duff, Catherine Gildiner, and Elizabeth Lesser.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Two walls against infection',
        text: 'Your body behaves like a well-run fortress. Warm, full of food, and welcoming to friendly guests, it also attracts hostile visitors. Bacteria and viruses slip past the walls when guards are tired, and your cells must rally to push them back. The body defends itself with two lines of defense, an innate system and an adaptive system, working together in coordinated waves.\n\nYou inherit the first line of defense, called the innate immune system. It springs into action within minutes but cannot tell one invader from another. Its job is to slow the attack and call for reinforcements. The second line is the adaptive immune system, which learns the exact shape of each enemy and remembers it for years. That memory is why you only catch certain diseases once. After the first illness, your body keeps a record of the intruder and a ready response for the next encounter.\n\nPicture a rusty nail that pierces your skin. Innate cells called macrophages rush in and swallow bacteria on the spot. They fight hard but tire quickly, so they send out chemical alarms. A second wave of cells, the neutrophils, arrives to finish the job. These cells are relentless, yet they are also reckless. They damage healthy tissue and even destroy themselves in the process, killing good cells alongside the bad ones as the wound tries to heal.\n\nFor you, the cut is small. For your cells, the same cut is a battlefield that demands a full response. The body keeps the cleanup going long after you put the band-aid on, sealing the skin, clearing debris, and rebuilding tissue. The next chapter follows the fight deeper into the wound.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Counterattack at the wound',
        text: 'Around the injury, the skin grows red and warm. Blood rushes in, swelling the tissue and pressing against nerves, which is how pain joins the picture. These five classic signs, redness, heat, swelling, loss of function, and pain, mark a healthy inflammatory response. Redness comes from extra blood flow. Heat is the same flow warming the area, which is uncomfortable for bacteria. Swelling follows naturally. Loss of function forces you to rest the hurt part. Pain is the nerve signal telling your brain that something needs care.\n\nShort bursts of inflammation save lives. Long, smoldering inflammation, however, sits at the root of heart disease, diabetes, and many cancers. Researchers now link it to more than half of all deaths worldwide, a striking share for a process most people ignore. Chronic inflammation is like a slow leak in a tire. You barely notice at first, but the damage adds up.\n\nA special squad called dendritic cells does not join the fight directly. Instead, they scoop up samples of the invader and carry them to lymph nodes, the intelligence centers of the body. There, helper T cells study the evidence and send antibodies back to the front lines. With new weapons in the battle, helper T cells rally the tired macrophages and pump fresh energy into the defense. Within days, the tide turns, and most civilian cells come out alive.\n\nA small wound on your skin is a full war inside your body.'
      },
      {
        title: 'When viruses come calling',
        text: 'Bacteria attack openly, but viruses use stealth. The influenza virus, for instance, slips inside healthy cells and hijacks their machinery. Each human cell stores DNA in a nucleus, the instruction manual for proteins. Once inside, the virus dumps its own genetic material into the cell and lets the cell copy it a thousand times over. The cell is now a factory for the enemy.\n\nFor a while, you feel only mild symptoms, a slight headache, maybe a tickle in the throat. The hijacked cells keep running their usual pattern, producing proteins and going about their day. Then fatigue hits, a fever rises, and the body aches. The hidden invasion has become a siege. Flu tends to arrive like a wall, while a cold often sneaks in over several days. The sudden collapse is a sign that the virus has spread far enough for the body to notice.\n\nCells fight back with interferons, which are proteins that warn neighbors to stop making new material. This pause slows the spread of the virus. Plasmacytoid dendritic cells then call for the rest of the immune system to join the fight. Even a stealthy virus cannot hide forever. Eventually the body catches up.\n\nA cold comes on slowly. The flu strikes like a storm.'
      },
      {
        title: 'The long war of HIV',
        text: 'Few diseases have caused as much fear as HIV. Untreated, the virus wears down the immune system until the body cannot fight even a mild infection. That final stage is known as AIDS. For a long time the abbreviations HIV and AIDS gave people goosebumps, and with good reason.\n\nHIV spreads through close contact or shared blood. It targets helper T cells, the same cells that organize the immune defense. First, it hides inside dendritic cells and rides them to the lymph nodes, where the helper T cells live. A short flu-like illness follows, then the virus goes quiet for years. Even a minor cold becomes a serious danger once AIDS has set in, because the body has almost no protection left.\n\nDuring the quiet phase, HIV multiplies inside lymph tissue. It mutates often, forcing the immune system to invent new defenses over and over. The chase drains the body of resources, and eventually the immune system gives up. Full-blown AIDS sets in, and any small infection becomes life-threatening. The patient is exposed to the outside world without guards.\n\nAs one writer put it, HIV behaves like a soldier who kills the victim, wears the skin, and walks through the city in daylight. The image is brutal but accurate.\n\nHIV is a retrovirus, meaning it can rewrite part of your DNA.'
      },
      {
        title: 'A balanced system beats a strong one',
        text: 'A sharper immune system sounds like a good thing, yet it carries risks. An overactive response can turn a minor cut into a chronic wound. Inflamed tissue can damage healthy cells for months or years. Pills and vitamins that promise to boost immunity may do more harm than good if you do not need them.\n\nA balanced immune system is the real goal. It should rise to meet a serious threat and settle down once the danger is gone. You can support this balance through daily habits. Eat plenty of vegetables and fruit. Move your body through walks or short runs. Rest when you are tired, and treat stress as a signal to slow down. Sleep, low stress, and good food keep the immune system steady.\n\nStrong immunity is not a goal on its own. Balance is. And balance starts with the small choices you make every day. Always talk to your doctor before reaching for pills or following advice from online experts.'
      }
    ]
  },
  'in-defense-of-food.json': {
    base: { id: 'in-defense-of-food', title: 'In Defense of Food', author: '', type: 'summary', addedAt: 1781652431458 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: 'Stop playing games with dinner',
        text: 'Modern life has sped up almost everything, including the way we eat. Bright minds in food science promised better health through clever processing, yet decades of strange new products suggest otherwise. Your grandparents likely remember fresh produce from local markets, while today most shoppers reach for packages with words they cannot pronounce.\n\nMany items on store shelves barely resemble the original food. Busy schedules push people toward whatever sits closest, and colorful claims on the box earn trust that hospital bills later contradict. How did we drift into this strange loop?\n\nMichael Pollan, a writer who has watched food culture shift for years, asked the same question. He wondered why obesity and illness kept rising even as nutrition science grew louder. His search led him to a hard truth: the noble effort to improve food had backfired, dragging shoppers along with it.\n\nIf any of this stirs your curiosity, take a bite of an apple and keep reading.'
      },
      {
        title: 'The marketing problem',
        text: 'The Western food industry is in the middle of a crisis of its own making. Nutritionists grow tired of labels that dress up profit motives as health benefits. The low-fat and nutrient-packed food trends of recent decades often turned out to be strange inventions rather than real solutions.\n\nStudies on the Western diet keep raising doubts. Pollan points out that nutrition science knows less than it admits, and the cost is paid by ordinary shoppers.\n\nIn the 1950s, families ate simple home-cooked meals that today would be called high-fat or even risky. Pollan remembers his grandmother cooking rich foods with butter and duck fat. His mother, raised on the new science, swapped those ingredients for vegetable oils sold as healthier. As each new warning hit the news, shoppers grew more anxious about food that did not wear a clean label.\n\nA plate of supermarket food today can become a pharmacy bill tomorrow.\n\nAn unwashed carrot from a backyard now feels strange to many city dwellers. Processed meals and chemically treated produce fill the shelves, and shoppers forget how food used to be grown or ripened. The focus on nutrients alone has bred an unhealthy obsession with eating right, sometimes called orthorexia.\n\nIsolated nutrients can mislead us. Raw beta-carotene, for example, has been linked to higher cancer risk in some studies.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Don\'t mess with nature',
        text: 'The modern idea of nutritionism took shape in the early 1800s. Scientists like William Prout and Justus von Liebig reduced human nourishment to a short list of proteins, fats, and carbohydrates. Their neat scheme ignored vitamins, minerals, and fiber, but it gave food companies an easy pitch. Marketers could pick a single nutrient, label it good or bad, and build a product around that claim.\n\nSoon, marketers split food into good and bad nutrients. Butter, eggs, and sugar fell out of favor, while processed products laced with added vitamins rose to the top. Calling traditional foods risky cleared the way for new packaged items, and government guidelines backed the trend. Margarine replaced butter, milk gained a dose of vitamin D in the lab, and shoppers were told to count nutrients instead of eating real meals.\n\nBy the 1930s, processed foods had their own section in most supermarkets. In 1938, the Food, Drug, and Cosmetic Act set standards for production and labeling. Shoppers who once balked at margarine eventually accepted it once the marketing machine shifted. As the years passed, the line between real and artificial food blurred. Farmers fed hens flaxseed to boost omega-3 in eggs, even though the body of research linking any single nutrient to disease kept coming up empty. The cash chase ended up undermining the original goal of better health, and people began to pay the price in new and surprising ways.\n\nTrying to improve on nature is a heavy responsibility. Most of the time, the changes that look like progress quietly add to the burden on our bodies.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Even good things go wrong in excess',
        text: 'As nutritionism spread, people stopped enjoying meals and started measuring them. Food became a delivery system for invisible nutrients, and shoppers were taught to chase the good ones while avoiding the bad.\n\nAmerican stores overflow with colorful options, and shoppers are tempted to try them all. Many of these products taste great but offer little real nourishment, so eating becomes a habit of indulgence rather than choice.\n\nThe catch is that the same people who feel guilty about eating chocolate cake also feel anxious about health. Studies show Americans link cake with guilt, while the French link it with celebration. Orthorexia, the obsession with healthy eating, keeps growing as a result.\n\nNutrition studies often fail for two reasons. They pull nutrients out of context, and participants keep sloppy food diaries. Nutrients work together, so separating them strips away their real value. Culture matters too. A Mediterranean diet practiced far from the Mediterranean lifestyle does not deliver the same results.\n\nIn one line from Michael Pollan, making food choices more scientific tends to empty them of their history and meaning.\n\nThe truth hides in the balance that science keeps trying to take apart.\n\nToo much of anything, even healthy food, can backfire.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Slow growth beats rushed perfection',
        text: 'The Western diet has finished a long run of industrialization and urbanization. Neither process is bad on its own, yet the scale has hurt how we eat and how we feel.\n\nNutrition researcher Kerin O\'Dea proved the point with a small study. She invited ten Aboriginal Australians to return to their ancestral land and live off it for seven weeks. Every participant lost weight, blood pressure dropped, and omega-3 levels rose to healthy ranges.\n\nAnother researcher, Weston A. Price, studied Aboriginal diets before World War II and found no single perfect menu. Each group ate what its land offered, whether mostly meat, fish, or greens, and all stayed remarkably healthy. Price argued that unprocessed food, whatever its makeup, was the common thread.\n\nModern studies of indigenous groups who still live on traditional food show almost no signs of diabetes, obesity, or heart disease. Once those same groups move to cities and eat processed diets, the diseases appear.\n\nGradual adaptation is the engine of evolution. Quick fixes rarely are.\n\nStill, diet alone cannot explain every health problem. Modern medicine has done a great deal to extend lives and ease chronic illness, yet longer lives also bring more age-related conditions. Modern farming has added another strain, since fertilizers push fast growth and strip produce of some nutrients. The result is food that looks fine but offers less than it once did.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Meet your food where it grows',
        text: 'So how can anyone eat healthier in this mess? The good news is that no exotic diet is required. The simpler and more natural the shift, the better it lasts. Food companies will keep selling processed products, and the medical world will keep selling pills. The real change begins at home.\n\nPollan reminds us that personal health is tied to the health of the land. One small problem in the food chain can ripple into a serious imbalance.\n\nAs researcher Denis Burkitt once said, the only way to reduce modern disease is to return to the diet and lifestyle of our ancestors.\n\nCity life and tight schedules make it hard to read every label at the store. Yet you do not have to. When ingredients sound strange, put the package back. Shop the edges of the store where whole foods live, and visit local farmers when you can.\n\nChoosing food with care is one of the most grown-up forms of self-respect.\n\nWhen it comes to what to eat, here are a few rules to keep in mind. Skip meat if you do not trust its source. Add more greens to your plate. Try wild foods like berries when they are safe and legal. Borrow from Greek, Japanese, or Indian traditions that have lasted for centuries. Avoid eating alone. Cook a few meals at home each week. Stop eating when you feel full.\n\nThose small habits can change how food feels and how the body responds.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Closing thoughts',
        text: 'Every big turn in history leaves a mark on how we eat. Food changes slowly, which is why shoppers often feel lost in the middle of a supermarket aisle.\n\nSince science stepped into the kitchen, the food on our plates has often gotten worse. Shoppers rarely understand nutrition well enough to push back, so food and drug companies keep selling complex products that treat diseases their other products help cause. Low-fat and low-carb diets were sold as the cure for obesity, yet they often made the problem worse. The truth is that no single magic food exists.\n\nNutrients behave like people. They work best in groups, not alone. Shopping for individual vitamins rarely pays off. Avoiding bad nutrients while ignoring balance only creates new problems. The simplest rule, that nothing is good in excess, still beats every trend.\n\nIt is no mystery why people in Greece, Italy, and France seem to enjoy food without gaining weight. Food culture, not just food science, sits at the heart of the answer. After all, meals are meant to be enjoyed, not counted.\n\nA few small changes can help. Treat every meal like a small ritual so cravings lose power. Build a healthy way to handle stress, such as walking, calling a friend, or sitting quietly. Do not ban treats, just listen to your body when it asks for one.'
      }
    ]
  },
  'in-order-to-live.json': {
    base: { id: 'in-order-to-live', title: 'In Order to Live', author: '', type: 'summary', addedAt: 1781661776551 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: 'Where silence speaks loudest',
        text: 'When most people think of North Korea, they picture hunger, isolation, and a cruel regime. The heavy government works hard to project an image of strength to outsiders and citizens alike. The gap between how the country looks from afar and how it feels up close is enormous.\n\nState propaganda has eaten away at critical thinking for generations. Only a few have caught a glimpse of life elsewhere and realized how wrong their own world has become. One man who never reached the free world passed that dream to his daughter. Years later she carried it from city to city, telling her story and giving voice to those still trapped behind the border. Her name is Yeonmi Park.\n\nNo story of suffering is more or less important than another when it comes to shining light on an oppressive regime. Yeonmi Park came from a relatively stable family by North Korean standards, so she was shocked to learn how much harder life was for many others. Her story is one window, not the only one. Read with care and form your own view.'
      },
      {
        title: 'A city perched on the edge',
        text: 'On October 4, 1993, a thin young woman gave birth two months early. The hard work of pregnancy had pushed her body too far. Doctors were unsure whether the baby would survive, especially in Hyesan, the coldest corner of North Korea. Hyesan sits on the Yalu River and has long served as a crossing point for smugglers, whose ranks swelled through the 1990s.\n\nThe North Korean economy collapsed after the Soviet Union fell. Without cheap fuel and fertilizer from Moscow and Beijing, even a basic harvest failed. Foreign aid mostly went to the army or was stolen before reaching ordinary people. The country struggled to breathe, much like the tiny newborn Yeonmi.\n\nIn the 1950s and 1960s, North Korea had been richer than the South, thanks to Soviet and Chinese aid and abundant minerals. By the 1980s, the planned economy had ground down, leaving people to fend for themselves. A black market sprang up, and even party officials could not stop it.\n\nYeonmi\'s family had high standing under the Kim regime, which gave them a strong songbun, or political class. That status collapsed when her grandfather\'s eldest son was convicted of a serious crime. In North Korea, one family member\'s offense drags everyone else down the ladder.\n\nYeonmi\'s father turned to smuggling to keep the family fed. On one trip across the border, he met his future wife, a woman who disliked capitalism but helped him anyway. Years later, while stealing coal to sell, she went into labor with Yeonmi.\n\nAnother well-known defector, Hyeonseo Lee, came from Hyesan. The city\'s border position helped her escape.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Growing up female in the North',
        text: 'As capitalism quietly filled North Korean towns, families learned to think in two directions at once. People cursed the Yankees at meetings and then went home to watch smuggled American films. Adult Yeonmi remembered watching Titanic as a girl and feeling that the world on the screen had nothing to do with the official story.\n\nThanks to a thriving black market, Yeonmi\'s family enjoyed short seasons of plenty. Her father grew his smuggling business and spent long stretches in Pyongyang. While he was away, a young woman helped him run things. His conscience pulled him home, yet the other woman later joined the household.\n\nYeonmi\'s mother was tougher than her husband. She kept the household steady and stood up to him during his drunken rages. When the regime finally caught her husband and sent him to a reeducation camp, she traveled to see him, leaving her daughters alone.\n\nSometimes a parent\'s love is measured by teaching a child to survive.\n\nYeonmi and her older sister Eunmi survived winter on roots and insects. Their mother sent Yeonmi to live with better-off relatives, then sold the house and moved them all to Kowon. She worked as a merchant and bribed her way through life. When Yeonmi turned eleven, she joined her mother and learned to trade.\n\nAs Yeonmi once put it, once you start trading for yourself, you start thinking for yourself.'
      },
      {
        title: 'No time to wait',
        text: 'By 2005, North Korea was changing fast. Thin CDs replaced bulky cassettes, making smuggling easier. Teenagers closed their blinds to watch forbidden movies. Some girls even dared to wear jeans or dye their hair, acts that could land them in prison. This new generation had no memory of a government that once provided for its people, so it trusted the regime less.\n\nYeonmi had been living with her mother and sister in Kowon, but police discovered the illegal house sale that funded the move. Her mother turned herself in for a few weeks at a reeducation camp. Around the same time, Yeonmi\'s sick father came home from captivity. His own brother turned him away because of his criminal record. Bribes eventually got the family back together in Hyesan.\n\nPoverty in Hyesan was now plain to see, especially when neighbors looked across the river at the lit-up Chinese side. Many young women slipped into China searching for a better life.\n\nYeonmi\'s family was starving. Her father\'s weak health kept him from working, and smuggling had grown harder. Her one bright spot was Chun Guen, a kind boy from a wealthy family who saw her as more than her low status. There was no sex education in North Korea, so their love stayed innocent.\n\nLove cannot replace food when survival is at stake.\n\nEven the promise of marriage could not save Yeonmi in a starving country. The chance to escape arrived the night her older sister Eunmi failed to come home. All she left behind was the address of a broker who promised to take Yeonmi into China.'
      },
      {
        title: 'A dangerous crossing',
        text: 'Smuggling was not the only business blooming along the Chinese border. Human trafficking grew just as fast. Many North Korean women fled across the river without knowing what waited. Once in China, they had no legal standing and were sold to rural men as wives or workers. Abuse was common.\n\nWhen Eunmi vanished, Yeonmi and her mother had no idea what they were walking into. They crossed the border quickly, under orders not to reveal their ages or family ties. The smugglers split them up almost at once.\n\nYeonmi had grown up sheltered. Hot showers, toothpaste, and sanitary products were all new to her. The horror began the first night, when her mother had to fend off a smuggler\'s advances. From that moment on, Yeonmi understood what sexual cruelty looked like.\n\nThey were separated. Her mother was sold to a farmer. Yeonmi was sold to a trafficker named Hongwei, who pressured her until she gave in. At her lowest point, she thought about ending her life.\n\nIn a twisted way, Hongwei did keep his word. He helped Yeonmi\'s father escape from North Korea, only for her father to die of cancer shortly after. Within a single year, Yeonmi and her mother had lived through violence, comfort, reunion, and loss. The hard times were not over.\n\nTragedy, more than joy, tends to show us who we really are.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Following the North Star',
        text: 'Living with a top trafficker was hard enough. When his business fell apart ahead of the Beijing Olympics, Yeonmi had to find a new protector. A man named Huang kept her close, hoping a soothsayer\'s prediction of a son would come true. To buy her mother\'s freedom, Yeonmi promised to stay. Instead, she and her mother fled to the city of Shenyang, where a fellow trafficking survivor named Myung Ok offered them work.\n\nIn Shenyang, mother and daughter found jobs chatting with strangers online, mostly South Korean men. Yeonmi picked it up faster and began earning real money. The work felt degrading, but it opened a door to a different future.\n\nThat door belonged to Hae Soon, another North Korean who had reached China. She arranged for Yeonmi and her mother to escape through Mongolia, the most common route for defectors. In the middle of the Gobi Desert, with a broken flashlight and a small group, they followed the North Star to avoid Chinese patrols.\n\nReaching Mongolia was not the end of the story. It was only the start of a new chapter called South Korea.\n\nIt is probably a mercy that we cannot see what is coming.'
      },
      {
        title: 'A new life with new rules',
        text: 'Fate finally smiled on Yeonmi. After she and her mother were moved from Mongolia to South Korea under the defector program, they spent time in two government facilities, the National Intelligence Center and the Hanawon Resettlement Center, before being released into society. A small apartment and a fresh ID felt like a miracle.\n\nStill, Yeonmi stuck out. She bounced between schools trying to catch up, only to meet low expectations from teachers and cold looks from classmates. Her North Korean accent set her apart. She turned to long hours of self-study, with George Orwell\'s Animal Farm standing out as a book that finally described her homeland.\n\nEven sweet beginnings can sour under real pressure.\n\nHer mother kept searching for Eunmi, who had been missing for years. A risky trip to China turned up nothing. Then a television producer invited Yeonmi to appear on a show about North Korean defectors called Now on My Way to Meet You. The family hoped Eunmi would see it and reach out. The reunion took longer than expected, but Eunmi did make it to South Korea on her own, surprised to find her family already there.\n\nYeonmi passed her GED and chose to study criminal justice. It was her mother\'s abusive boyfriend who pushed her toward that major, but the path she took soon surprised even her.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Finding a voice in a strange world',
        text: 'North Korean students face a steep climb in South Korean universities. The knowledge gap and intense study culture push many to drop out. Yeonmi felt that pressure early. She had to impress the admissions office and then study harder than her classmates. Computers and physical tests were her weak spots in the criminal justice program at Dongguk University, and she sometimes fainted during training.\n\nThe hardest part was English. She refused to give up, channeling the same stubbornness that carried her out of North Korea.\n\nEducation is the freedom of the people and the nightmare of tyrants.\n\nShe devoured audiobooks and TED talks. When she finally traveled to the United States, the scary Yankees of her childhood turned out to be parents with kids and teenagers who laughed. A Christian youth group took her to a homeless shelter, even though she was not religious. The trip taught her compassion and showed her a new calling.\n\nAs Yeonmi later wrote, everyone has their own desert. We may not all cross the same sand, but we all have to cross something to find a purpose.\n\nShe gave talks at the Canadian Maple International School and the One Young World Summit. By telling the truth about North Korea, she became a voice for those who lived in silence. Then one day she heard a voice back. It was her sister. Today, Yeonmi and the two most important women in her life are still walking that road together.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Closing thoughts',
        text: 'The Bible says God will not let you be tested beyond your strength, and will always provide a way through. Yeonmi had no use for religion in a country where the only gods were the Kims. Even as an adult, she could not make herself follow any faith. She found strength in her own story.\n\nWhen others asked for her help, she answered from personal experience, a hungry childhood, years without freedom, trafficking, and the loneliness of standing out. She never needed Christian humility. She needed faith in herself.\n\nThe great force that carried Yeonmi through every hardship was trust in her own power and love for her family.\n\nShe was born staring at the bright lights of a country she was told she could never have. That glimpse of a different life may have planted the courage that carried her across borders. Her journey has taken her from North Korea to China to South Korea to the United States. Complicated relationships, painful choices, and threats from her homeland shaped the woman she became. After one speech, a stranger thanked her for teaching the meaning of the word inspire. That word now sits at the heart of her work.\n\nFor readers who want to keep learning, Hyeonseo Lee\'s memoir The Girl with Seven Names tells another defector\'s story. Documentaries such as Inside North Korea, Crossing the Line, A State of Mind, and Songs from the North offer further windows into the country Yeonmi left behind.'
      }
    ]
  },
  'in-the-flo.json': {
    base: { id: 'in-the-flo', title: 'In the FLO', author: '', type: 'summary', addedAt: 1781661909935 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: 'Hormones open the door to a fuller life',
        text: 'As a teen, Alisa Vitti pushed herself to the top of every class and joined every club she could. The habits carried into college and then into her first jobs, but they came at a cost. She gained weight, struggled to sleep, and her periods stopped following any pattern.\n\nIn college she read an obstetrics article that linked her symptoms to polycystic ovary syndrome, also called PCOS. Tests confirmed the diagnosis. That diagnosis pushed her to create a system she calls the Cycle Syncing Method, a way to live with female energy instead of against it. Vitti believes every woman benefits from understanding biohacking and learning what her body can do when it works with her hormones.\n\nA woman who lives in tune with her hormonal cycle can tap into energy and potential she never knew she had. This summary explains how that works and what changes when you stop fighting your body.\n\nSyncing with your natural cycle can transform how you feel day to day.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Men and women run on different clocks',
        text: 'Myths about women\'s bodies fill the media. Some girls grow up treating periods as something shameful rather than natural. Not knowing how your body works can lead to neglect and worse health later on. The first step toward feeling better is learning the truth about your reproductive system.\n\nHealth advice often claims to be neutral, yet men and women respond very differently. Many women feel bad about their cycles, their moods, and even being female. Common myths include the ideas that PMS is unavoidable, that cramps are normal, that the pill always regulates cycles, and that skipping periods is fine.\n\nResearch shows PMS usually comes from an imbalance of estrogen. Eating the right foods and aligning with the cycle can make PMS far more manageable.\n\nThe patriarchy has spread these myths for centuries, leaving women out of research and treatment while shaping culture around them.\n\nMen run on a 24-hour hormonal cycle. Testosterone and cortisol peak in the morning, giving men energy and drive. Levels dip after lunch, leaving them calmer. By night their hormones fall and they relax. Women follow a much longer cycle, yet daily life still pushes them onto the same 24-hour clock, which costs them energy.\n\nPMS, when left untreated, can raise the risk of cancer, diabetes, and dementia after menopause.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Women can step off the 24-hour clock',
        text: 'Every living system runs on cycles, and the human body is no different. Women of reproductive age carry two clocks, one that matches the 24-hour day and another that follows the monthly cycle. When these clocks work together, energy, health, and productivity rise. When they fight each other, everything feels harder.\n\nThe circadian clock follows the sun. The hormonal clock follows the menstrual cycle and lasts about 28 days. That longer cycle breaks into four phases, the follicular phase, the ovulatory phase, the luteal phase, and the menstrual phase.\n\nThe hormonal clock shapes a woman\'s health far more than the daily one. It touches the brain, the immune system, and the metabolism, giving both boosts and challenges across the month.\n\nThe 24-hour and 28-day clocks weave together and affect each other constantly.\n\nWhen a woman respects both clocks, she makes the most of her energy. When she ignores them, she ends up drained. The change requires daily check-ins, careful planning, and permission to rest.\n\nLeaving the 24-hour mindset takes daily work. Track your choices, keep your to-do list realistic, and build in breaks for things you enjoy. Step outside work and connect with people. That habit supports both clocks.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Your body moves through four phases',
        text: 'No pill can match the steady energy of balanced hormones. Hormone levels change every day, so a fixed daily routine will not serve a woman well. Self-care, diet, and exercise all need to bend with the cycle. Biohacking the body means working with its natural rhythm.\n\nThe endocrine system is the control center that runs the body through hormones.\n\nA few key hormones drive the cycle. Estrogen shapes mood and energy. Progesterone balances estrogen. Follicle-stimulating hormone and luteinizing hormone trigger ovulation. Insulin manages blood sugar. Cortisol handles stress. When these fall out of balance, periods suffer and the cycle loses its power.\n\nFour phases repeat each month and each brings a different kind of strength. The follicular phase runs about seven to ten days and is a time to plan as hormones settle. The ovulatory phase lasts three to four days, when a surge of estrogen and luteinizing hormone releases an egg and boosts communication. The luteal phase lasts ten to fourteen days, and rising hormones sharpen focus, which makes it the perfect time to finish tasks. The menstrual phase lasts three to seven days and is a moment to slow down, reflect, and notice what the body is saying.\n\nA menstrual cycle influences the brain, immune system, and metabolism. Knowing the phases helps a woman plan her work and understand her moods.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Food shapes the quality of your life',
        text: 'Cycle syncing may go against what many women were taught. Education, medicine, and culture have all encouraged women to push through their bodies\' signals. Reconnecting with the natural cycle builds a deeper relationship with the body. It asks for patient observation and honest feedback.\n\nSyncing with the cycle is not a quick fix. It is a steady practice that changes you from the inside out.\n\nFood fuels the body and influences hormones more than most people realize. Studies show that micronutrients like vitamin D and calcium lower the risk of PMS. Avocado, pumpkin seeds, olive oil, chickpeas, and leafy greens supply nutrients that support fertility and energy. Pair that with regular movement and a healthy body mass index, and the cycle responds well.\n\nAs Alisa Vitti has said, most women never hear that the food on their plate is shaping their symptoms.\n\nEach phase asks for different fuel. Fresh, colorful foods lift energy in the follicular phase. Vegetables and fruit bring antioxidants that support metabolism during ovulation. Slow-burning carbs, fiber, and greens steady blood sugar in the luteal phase. Proteins and healthy fats cushion the body through the hormone drop of the menstrual phase.\n\nIt also helps to cut back on caffeine. Caffeine makes cramps worse, lowers fertility, and feeds cyst growth.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Smarter workouts beat harder ones',
        text: 'Your body changes every day. Forcing the same workout every day ignores those signals. Work with your cycle instead of against it.\n\nTraining with the cycle lets a woman reach her peak without burning out. Strength training works best in the follicular phase, when the body builds muscle faster. The first half of the cycle brings energy and power. The menstrual phase drains energy, and tough endurance work only deepens the fatigue.\n\nFollicular and ovulatory phases give the most energy to spend. Cardio and lean muscle building fit well here. The luteal phase still carries some fuel, but it fades. Skip the hardest cardio, focus on strength, and add gentle stretching. During the menstrual phase, rest comes first. Walk, stretch, sleep more, and save the tough sessions for later.\n\nPlan workouts around how each phase feels.\n\nDiet and gym culture push women to give their all every day. That mindset ignores real biology. Some days a five-hour hike feels easy. Other days a short stretch is plenty. Listen to the body. Working out when you are already drained only adds to the fatigue.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Understanding the body makes periods easier',
        text: 'Periods can feel complicated. They arrive at odd times, bring pain, and interrupt plans. They do not have to feel that way every month. The more a woman knows about her body, the better she can care for it. When she matches her activities to each phase, she gets more done with less stress.\n\nEach month, an ovary releases a mature egg. Sperm race toward it, yet only one will win. That process teaches a quiet lesson: you do not always have to chase. When you are in the right place, things find you. Trust the body and the timing.\n\nThe organs of the body are connected and work together as one system.\n\nA few small steps can soften a painful period. Keep blood sugar steady, because spikes unsettle hormones. Care for the adrenal glands and keep cortisol balanced. Support the organs that clear waste, including the skin, liver, gut, and lymphatic system.\n\nPeriod problems are signs of a deeper imbalance, not random bad luck. Pay attention to the cycle and practice steady self-care. Try cycle-specific foods and adjust activities as needed.\n\nAs Gloria Steinem once put it, do not try to make women fit the world. Make the world fit women.'
      },
      {
        title: 'The cycle can power your work',
        text: 'A woman who pays attention will notice her body feels different across the month. Some days she loves a new project. Other days she cannot sit through another meeting. Most workplaces ignore these shifts, so women push through long hours and trade health for output. That approach always backfires in the long run.\n\nEach phase brings a different working strength. The follicular phase lifts creativity and planning. Rising estrogen boosts memory and motivation, which makes it a great time to design strategy and solve problems. The ovulatory phase brings openness and easy communication. Estrogen peaks, so it is the best window for collaboration and building relationships. The luteal phase is the phase of completion. It is the right time to wrap up open tasks. The menstrual phase invites review and reflection. Both sides of the brain sync up, creating a clean space to evaluate direction and reset.\n\nTuning in to these energies helps a woman focus on her goals. No phase locks her into only one kind of work. Each phase sets up the conditions to do her best at that moment. Following the cycle lets existing skills shine and adds fuel to the biggest ambitions.\n\nEach phase brings a different and valuable kind of contribution to the workplace.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Sync sex with the cycle',
        text: 'Surveys show that more than half of women are not fully satisfied with their sex life. The issue is not just frequency, but also timing and quality. Diet, exercise, and the monthly cycle all shape libido. Tuning into the cycle can lift desire and make intimacy richer. A partner\'s cycle also matters when planning sex around both rhythms.\n\nSex feels better when women follow their hormones. The four stages of arousal, including initial arousal, plateau, climax, and recovery, are worth learning about. Libido also shifts with the cycle, so there is no reason to feel guilt on low-desire days. Solo pleasure is healthy too and helps a woman stay aware of her own body.\n\nSex lifts the heart rate and improves blood flow, which supports overall health.\n\nFoods rich in magnesium, zinc, probiotics, vitamin B, and omega-3s can lift libido for any gender. Sharing cycle information with a partner helps both people plan for better intimacy. Intimacy is not only about sex. Date nights, long talks, and shared activities deepen the bond.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Closing thoughts',
        text: 'Women tap into real power when they understand their bodies. Marriage, work, motherhood, and sex all feel better when she stops chasing perfection and puts well-being first. There is room to feel as carefree as a child. Puberty and periods are not a curse. They can change a woman\'s life for the better.\n\nLiving by the 24-hour clock alone no longer works. The circadian clock must move in step with the menstrual cycle. That shift asks for new habits, a willingness to listen to the body, and a commitment to respond to what it needs. The more aligned a woman is with this inner clock, the more settled she feels in her body and her life.\n\nHealthy, balanced hormones help a woman show up as a better mother, partner, leader, and human. None of it happens by accident. It takes willingness to know where she is in her cycle, eat with intention, and move with care. Over time the results become clear. Along the way, caffeine, hormonal birth control, and alcohol are best avoided because they disturb the hormonal balance.\n\nChange is possible. The 28-day cycle can be used as a real guide.\n\nFor a fun challenge, grab a calendar and mark where you are in your cycle each day. Write down how your body feels and which foods and activities help at each stage. Build a small habit of noticing, and let the insights grow from there.'
      }
    ]
  },
  'inner-engineering.json': {
    base: { id: 'inner-engineering', title: 'Inner Engineering', author: '', type: 'summary', addedAt: 1781662015836 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: 'Set aside trendy advice and meet your deeper nature',
        text: 'Modern self-help can feel like taking laxatives for a cough. It does not solve the real problem and just keeps the cough locked inside. That is why the word guru has gotten a strange reputation. A true guru is meant to bring light, not push a belief system.\n\nThe modern world keeps telling us to live in the moment. Yet we are always in some moment. There is no escaping it. Telling yourself not to worry about the past or future goes against the natural movement of the mind.\n\nYou cannot truly banish worry about the past or the future because your mind runs on those very thoughts.\n\nPositive thinking has become a tired slogan. Forcing yourself to feel good shuts out the negative feelings that also deserve attention. A steady practice of staying open to all emotions builds a stronger optimism in the long run.\n\nA real transformation is not about changing your values or habits overnight. It is about noticing the older version of you that is ready to fall away.\n\nA guru is not a drill sergeant. Think of one as a GPS for the path: Guru Pathfinding System.\n\nIn Sanskrit, the word sadhana refers to a tool or practice for inner growth.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Joy lives inside, not outside',
        text: 'People spend their lives chasing joy, and it can feel hard to catch. Humans are complicated, so simple comfort is not enough. Survival is the baseline. Once hunger, cold, and thirst are out of the way, something else must take over.\n\nThat something is pleasantness, the feel of health, calm, and a friendly environment. Pleasantness pushes you toward your best work. Much of the time, pleasantness seems to come from the outside, which is why we keep chasing external rewards. Real tools that tune the inner world work better.\n\nExternal help can take you part of the way. Staying there is up to you. Every sight, sound, and thought is something your mind builds. If the mind builds it, the mind can also change it.\n\nYour experience is your creation, so you hold the power to reshape it.\n\nHappiness and peace are not magic. They are chemistry. Even simple acts like breathing feel good when you pay attention inside rather than running from discomfort.\n\nMany people frame peace as a spiritual trophy far away from daily life. That framing misses the point. Joy is not a goal but a basic human need. When life is seen as a process you are part of, bliss shows up more often.\n\nThere is no border on your inner world. When you find the outer world reflected inside, you feel limitless. That is not a secret trick reserved for monks. It is a natural human state.\n\nA story is often told of a tourist who asked a local boy for directions to a yoga center. The boy smiled and said it was twenty-five thousand miles away, but only four if he turned around. The same is true on the journey inward. You turn within to express joy rather than chase it.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Responsibility is your real power',
        text: 'When life gets uncomfortable, it is easy to blame destiny or divine will. You wonder why the universe is making you suffer. Yet when hunger hits, you plan a meal. The same goes for every other trouble. You take responsibility and act.\n\nPolio is a clear example. Many once called it God\'s will. Modern medicine has nearly wiped it out and saved countless lives.\n\nHumans can shape their lives, but only after they know who they really are. The common mistake is to think you are your body, your thoughts, or the things you have collected. If that is all you are, you have not yet met yourself.\n\nThe line between ignorance and enlightenment runs through your awareness of choice.\n\nTaking responsibility for your life does not guarantee that things go your way. Pain still comes, and you are the one who needs the cure. The key is to stop letting outside events run you over.\n\nYour peace depends on how you respond. When you react on autopilot, circumstances take the wheel. When you respond with care, you keep the wheel. Let us break down what responsibility really means.\n\nResponsibility is often confused with blame. They are different ideas. Responsibility is your ability to respond. When you claim it, you start finding solutions and step into your power.\n\nReactivity leaves you stuck. Anger does not fix anything and often makes the situation worse. It also damages the body and cuts you off from a sense of belonging.\n\nResponsibility is not the same as action. It creates the space for action. It also does not mean you can do anything.\n\nAccountability means you steer your own life once you see that it is open. The range of actions is always limited, but the willingness to take responsibility is the real difference maker.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Yoga is the science of inner joy',
        text: 'Most people think of yoga as exercise, but the science of yoga is much wider than that.\n\nIn the words of Sadhguru Jaggi Vasudev, the science of yoga is the science of being in perfect alignment, in harmony, in sync with existence.\n\nYoga wakes up energy and reveals new capacities. Most of all, it joins the self and the rest of life. The sense of oneness is its purpose, the feeling that everything is part of you.\n\nMany believe the self is just body, mind, and energy. Yoga describes five sheaths. The physical body is the one you feed. The mental body sits close to the physical. The energy body powers both. The etheric body sits beyond perception and bridges the physical and the nonphysical. The bliss body is hard to describe in words.\n\nThe fifth sheath, called anandamaya kosha, comes from the word for bliss. It is not about chasing happiness inside. It opens up once the other sheaths are in harmony. Bliss arrives when you reach a dimension beyond ordinary existence.\n\nDo not worry if this sounds reserved for saints. The path begins with what you already know, and the body\'s limits do not block inner joy. Anyone can practice.\n\nYoga goes far beyond exercise. Karma yoga moves the body. Gnana yoga works with intelligence. Kriya yoga transforms energy. Bhakti yoga works with feelings and devotion. Each person carries a different mix, and they need to work together.\n\nYoga does not give superpowers. It reveals the powers you already have as a human being.\n\nWith the map set, we can look at specific practices and reframe old ideas to reach your deepest nature.\n\nIn yoga, the gesture of putting the hands together, called namaskar, is meant to balance energies such as masculine and feminine and to invite inner harmony.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Listen to the body to live better',
        text: 'Most of the body runs on autopilot. Organs work like a complex machine. The nonphysical side can clash with the physical. People get caught between two instincts: the urge to protect the body and the urge to expand beyond it.\n\nTry this small exercise to feel balance. Sit near a plant and notice that it breathes in what you breathe out. After a few minutes you may feel a quiet connection to the plant and to everything around you.\n\nYour body can either hold you back or become a tool for inner growth.\n\nMind and body are deeply linked. Taking care of the spine and limbs shapes the mind, but the process must stay gentle. Listen to feelings by simply sitting with the body. Slow the breath and let any practice deepen on its own. Never force the body into painful shapes.\n\nFor many, the body feels like a wall. Awareness of its rhythms changes that. The body is built from food, so nutrition matters. Learn what fuels you well, and remember that healthy eating is about what works with your digestion.\n\nStart with a little more raw fruit and vegetables and notice how you feel. A simple target is to make half of each meal plants.\n\nSleep matters too. It is the body\'s way of recharging. Other calming activities can also restore you, whether walking, sitting quietly, or focused work. Rest is not limited to lying down.\n\nThere is no fixed rule about how many hours to sleep or how much to eat. The right amount depends on the day. Trust what you already know.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Set aside labels and unite with life',
        text: 'The human mind runs countless processes every second. For most people, it feels like a tangle. Once you learn how to direct it, the mind becomes a useful tool.\n\nThe intellect helps you make decisions that keep you alive, but overthinking keeps you from living. Separate the mind from yourself and freedom shows up.\n\nMemories and possessions belong to you, but they are not you. Step back from them often. As that habit grows, joy gets closer.\n\nPinning your intellect to a single label, like a nationality or a gender, becomes a heavy burden. It narrows you. Try this exercise to spot those limits. Remove distractions and think for an hour. Notice where the mind goes and you will see the identity you have built.\n\nThe aim of the exercise is awareness, not effort. Awareness is not the same as being alert. It is part of who you are. You know life by being aware of existence. You cannot force the state, but it opens up when the sheaths are in harmony.\n\nAwareness lets you focus and reach what you want.\n\nA common mistake is splitting heart and head. Yoga teaches that you are one. The mind is a union of thoughts and emotions.\n\nIt also helps to drop the split between good and bad. That split comes from beliefs handed down over generations and traps you in a small frame. Existence itself does not run on labels of right and wrong. When that truth lands, you gain the acceptance and flexibility to touch realms beyond the physical.\n\nFinally, learn to enjoy not knowing. Life is vast, and the more you try to pin it down, the more questions pile up. Analyzing everything puts you on the outside looking in. Devote yourself to life and you will feel at one with it.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Take charge of your karma',
        text: 'Modern science says everything is energy shaped by analysis. Religion says everything comes from belief in God. A yogi chooses neither. A yogi wants to experience.\n\nMost people hear the word karma and think of punishment. Karma is really the buildup of your choices. You can take back control instead of letting karma run you.\n\nYour experience of life sets its quality, not outside forces.\n\nHere is one way to step free from karma\'s grip. Spend a few minutes each day imagining you are the only person in the world. Meditate on what truly matters. You will connect with yourself rather than the impressions you have collected.\n\nKarma acts on the outside, the body and mind. Kriya is an inner action without form. It is harder but also freeing. With the right guidance, steady practice, and patience, you can become the master of your energy and your life.\n\nToday, many people talk about aligning chakras, or energy centers. Chakras have a physical side, while nadis do not. Nadis are the seventy-two channels energy moves through. Awareness can reveal the entire map.\n\nAll nadis branch from three main channels. Pingala is masculine and logical, outgoing in nature. Ida is feminine and reflective, tied to intuition. Sushumna runs through the center and stands apart from the other two. In Sushumna, the inner self is free from outside influence.\n\nThe chakras form a triangle where the three channels meet. Energy flows through them with different intensity depending on which one dominates. Many yogic practices help you shift energy between chakras, which takes courage. A trusted guru can be a real help on this path.\n\nA master cannot hand over the realization directly. You have to arrive at it yourself. Still, much sits in remote sacred places, available in the form of energy. Mount Kailash, Kedarnath, and Kumara Parvat have all opened spiritual insight for many visitors.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Closing thoughts',
        text: 'Joy can become a steady companion when you learn to look inward. Looking back across history, we live in the most comfortable era yet. Technology and medicine have come far. Yet even with all this comfort, we are not the happiest generation. That gap shows that the answer is not out there.\n\nThe truth is that we can solve many of the world\'s hardest problems. So what is in the way?\n\nMost people stay focused on outer circumstances. They worry about limits, failures, and even successes. When joy is found within, the maturity and compassion to face global issues show up on their own. If you want to help the world, begin with yourself. Only you are responsible for your own joy. Karma is your creation, and you choose what your life holds.\n\nEven without practicing every exercise in this book, you can step out of the ordinary and walk a freer path. Look for the layers of your identity and pick up new perspectives.\n\nWhen you stop blocking your own happiness, the answers to every challenge begin to show up.\n\nWhen stress shows up, try a small exercise to balance your chakra movement. Open your eyes and fix your gaze about eight inches away from the point between your brows. Picture each chakra for twelve to forty-eight minutes, depending on how steady your focus is. The more time you spend in this meditation, the more aligned the chakras become. This kriya yoga practice opens access to the etheric layer of the self.'
      }
    ]
  }
};
